# Cloudflare Pages headers. Buildless app with STABLE filenames (no content hashes), so a long
# browser TTL shadows new deploys with the cached old modules until it expires — worse here
# because the experience is embedded in a cross-origin <iframe>, so even a parent hard-refresh
# doesn't bust the iframe's cached subresources.
#
# Two Pages quirks learned the hard way:
#  - A LEADING-splat pattern (/*, /*.ext) matches greedily across slashes, but a trailing
#    /dir/* splat matched NOTHING here (/js/* left the module graph on the default max-age=14400).
#    So target by extension with leading-splat patterns.
#  - When several rules match one file their headers are COMBINED (no "most specific wins"), so a
#    file must match exactly ONE Cache-Control rule — the patterns below are non-overlapping.

# JS (including the vendored three.min.js) + HTML: always revalidate. Stable filenames mean a tiny
# 304 via ETag when nothing changed, and the new file immediately after a deploy — never stale code.
/*.js
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate
/*.html
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

# Textures (.webp) match no other rule, so this is the only one they hit — cache a day; bump/purge
# in the Cloudflare dashboard on the rare swap (filenames are stable).
/*.webp
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400
